# Backend Upgradation Plan

Provide a brief description of the problem, any background context, and what the change accomplishes.
This upgrade will transition the Resume Builder backend from a standard prototype to a robust, scalable, enterprise-grade architecture. Phase 2 focuses on hardening the server against XSS, NoSQL injections, and DOS attacks while implementing rigorous input validation. Phase 3 focuses on horizontal scalability, eliminating the main thread CPU bottlenecks when handling asynchronous Gemini AI completions and synchronous PDF parsing.

## User Review Required

> [!WARNING]
> **Client-Side Changes:** Moving to a Queue (BullMQ) means the `POST /api/ai/analyze` route will no longer return the AI analysis directly. It will return `202 Accepted` with a `jobId`. The frontend React application *must* be updated to continuously poll a status endpoint (`GET /api/ai/status/:jobId`) to get the finalized result.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Redis Requirement:** BullMQ requires a running Redis instance (e.g. Upstash, Aiven, or local Docker).

## Proposed Changes

### Dependencies Layer
We will install necessary security and schema-validation packages.
#### [NEW] Dependencies
- `helmet`: Sets secure HTTP headers.
- `express-mongo-sanitize`: Prevents basic NoSQL injection.
- `zod`: Industry-standard schema validation.

---

### Phase 1 & 3: Scalability & Queueing

#### [NEW] `server/queue/aiQueue.js`
- Instantiate the BullMQ `Queue` instance to accept incoming requests.

#### [NEW] `server/workers/aiWorker.js`
- Create a BullMQ `Worker` instance explicitly for heavy tasks.
- Move the `pdf-parse` execution and Google Gemini execution into this worker.
- Configure `concurrency: 2` (or your preferred number) so the server never hits the Gemini 429 rate limit.

#### [MODIFY] `server/controllers/aiController.js`
- Break up the endpoints.
- Update `/analyze` to dispatch tasks to the BullMQ queue (`await aiQueue.add('analyze-resume', data)`).
- Provide immediate `202 Accepted` HTTP responses.
- Implement an endpoint: `GET /api/ai/status/:id` to check whether BullMQ has completed the job.

#### [NEW] `server/cluster.js`
- Implement Node's native `cluster` module.
- It will fork the Node process `os.cpus().length` times ensuring your Vercel/VPS server utilizes all available multithreading capacity for processing standard HTTP requests.

---

### Phase 2: Security & Validation

#### [MODIFY] `server/server.js`
- Integrate `helmet()` middleware globally.
- Integrate `mongoSanitize()` middleware globally.
- Upgrade the Global Error Handler to specifically parse `ZodError` formats and Custom HTTP Error classes, providing detailed field-specific validation warnings back to the frontend.

#### [NEW] `server/middlewares/validateRequest.js`
- Create a reusable middleware that accepts a Zod schema to validate `req.body` or `req.query` automatically before executing controller logic.

#### [NEW] `server/utils/AppError.js`
- Create a unified Error mechanism that extends the native Node.js `Error` object, allowing controllers to do `throw new AppError('Not Found', 404)` cleanly.

#### [MODIFY] `server/routes/...` (Where Multer is used)
- Impose strict `limits: { fileSize: 2 * 1024 * 1024 }` (2MB) on `multer` memory storage to prevent RAM exhaustion.

